// Functional / Applied Physiology Exam (100 questions, 5 options each, A–E)
// { n, section, text, options:[5], answer: index (0=A..4=E) }
const FUNCTIONAL = [
  // ---- Section 1: Applied Physiology and Function (Q1–50) ----
  { n:1, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"When body temperature drops, temperature-sensing neurons detect the change and send a signal to the brain. The brain interprets this and sends a signal to skeletal muscles to involuntarily shiver. In this homeostatic feedback loop, what is the specific functional role of the skeletal muscles?", options:["They act as the sensor to detect the temperature drop in the environment.","They act as the control center to interpret the temperature change.","They act as the effector to generate heat and counteract the original stimulus.","They act as the afferent pathway to send signals back to the brain.","They establish the normal set-point for the body's internal temperature."], answer:2 },
  { n:2, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"Congestive heart failure (CHF) is often worsened by a physiological loop where decreased blood flow causes the kidneys to retain more water. This excess water volume puts more stress on the heart, which further reduces blood flow. Functionally, why is this considered a \"positive\" feedback loop?", options:["Because it involves multiple organ systems working together to save the patient.","Because the response enhances and intensifies the original stimulus (decreased blood flow) rather than reversing it.","Because the body is successfully attempting to return to a normal set-point.","Because water retention is always a positive biological mechanism for survival.","Because the heart is acting as both the sensor and the effector simultaneously."], answer:1 },
  { n:3, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"In a clinical case study, a patient (Luis M.) experiences metabolic acidosis with a dangerously low blood pH due to severe fluid loss. Functionally, why are bicarbonate ions administered to this patient via IV fluids?", options:["To directly destroy the stomach virus causing the initial fluid loss.","To act as a buffer by absorbing excess H+ ions and resisting drastic changes in blood pH.","To permanently stop the kidneys from producing urine to conserve water.","To dissolve the excess glucose in his bloodstream.","To replace the red blood cells lost during dehydration."], answer:1 },
  { n:4, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"Why are electrolytes (such as sodium and potassium ions) functionally critical for cellular survival and systemic homeostasis?", options:["They are the primary structural macromolecules used to build the cell membrane.","They bind together to form the cell's genetic DNA code.","They maintain electrical membrane potentials, allowing for nerve impulses and muscle contractions.","They act as the body's primary source of long-term stored energy.","They secrete the protective mucous lining of the digestive tract."], answer:2 },
  { n:5, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"During digestion, water molecules are chemically inserted into the bonds of large carbohydrate polymers to break them down into absorbable simple sugars. What is the functional name for this specific chemical reaction?", options:["Dehydration synthesis","Anabolic reaction","Hydrolysis reaction","Exchange reaction","Isotope decay"], answer:2 },
  { n:6, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"Enzymes are biological catalysts composed of proteins. Functionally, how do enzymes speed up the chemical reactions necessary to sustain human life?", options:["By increasing the temperature of the cell to the boiling point.","By permanently changing their own structure to become part of the final product.","By lowering the activation energy required for the reaction to occur.","By converting simple sugars directly into nucleic acids.","By reversing the direction of all cellular catabolic reactions."], answer:2 },
  { n:7, section:"Cells & Transport", text:"A cell needs to move sodium ions out of its cytoplasm, pushing them against a steep concentration gradient. Which cellular mechanism must it utilize to functionally accomplish this?", options:["Simple diffusion","Facilitated diffusion through a leaky channel","Osmosis","Primary active transport using an ATP-powered pump","Phagocytosis"], answer:3 },
  { n:8, section:"Cells & Transport", text:"What is the immediate physiological consequence to red blood cells if a patient is accidentally given an IV fluid that is pure, sterile water (extremely hypotonic to their intracellular fluid)?", options:["The cells will rapidly shrink and shrivel (crenation) to conserve water.","Water will rapidly move into the cells via osmosis, causing them to swell and potentially burst (hemolysis).","The cells will begin to actively pump water out to maintain osmotic balance.","The cells will immediately divide via mitosis to handle the extra fluid volume.","Nothing; pure water is perfectly isotonic to blood plasma."], answer:1 },
  { n:9, section:"Cells & Transport", text:"Certain white blood cells act as the body's defense mechanism by completely engulfing whole bacteria or large cellular debris. What is the specific functional term for this \"cell eating\" mechanism?", options:["Pinocytosis","Receptor-mediated endocytosis","Phagocytosis","Exocytosis","Facilitated diffusion"], answer:2 },
  { n:10, section:"Cells & Transport", text:"Within a muscle cell, a specialized smooth endoplasmic reticulum (the sarcoplasmic reticulum) serves a critical function. What is its primary physiological role?", options:["To synthesize all the structural proteins (actin and myosin) for the cell.","To digest old, worn-out organelles using acid hydrolases.","To store, retrieve, and release calcium ions (Ca2+) necessary for contraction.","To generate massive amounts of ATP using oxygen.","To package and ship proteins out of the cell via exocytosis."], answer:2 },
  { n:11, section:"Homeostasis & Chemistry", text:"Which statement best describes the functional difference between anabolism and catabolism?", options:["Anabolism breaks down large molecules to release energy, while catabolism requires energy to build large molecules.","Anabolism occurs only in the digestive tract, while catabolism occurs only in the brain.","Anabolism requires energy to synthesize large molecules, while catabolism breaks large molecules apart to release energy.","Anabolism solely utilizes osmosis, while catabolism solely utilizes active transport.","Anabolism refers to positive feedback loops, while catabolism refers to negative feedback loops."], answer:2 },
  { n:12, section:"Cells & Transport", text:"From a functional standpoint, why do somatic cells in the human body undergo mitosis?", options:["To produce genetically unique sex cells (sperm and eggs) for reproduction.","To synthesize completely new, entirely different types of tissues during adulthood.","To generate exact genetic clones for tissue growth, maintenance, and the repair of damaged cells.","To convert chemical energy from glucose into functional ATP.","To actively transport large macromolecules across the cell membrane."], answer:2 },
  { n:13, section:"Tissues", text:"Epithelial tissue is completely avascular (lacks blood vessels). How does it functionally obtain the necessary oxygen and nutrients to survive and regenerate rapidly?", options:["It synthesizes its own oxygen and nutrients via photosynthesis.","It obtains them through simple diffusion from blood vessels located in the underlying connective tissue.","It relies strictly on the evaporation of sweat to draw in nutrients from the environment.","It absorbs all necessary nutrients directly from the bone marrow.","It utilizes gap junctions to steal nutrients from nervous tissue."], answer:1 },
  { n:14, section:"Tissues", text:"What is the physiological function of the microvilli commonly found on the apical surface of simple columnar epithelial cells in the digestive tract?", options:["To sweep trapped debris and mucus out of the airway.","To generate electrical action potentials to stimulate digestion.","To dramatically increase the surface area available to maximize nutrient absorption.","To secrete large amounts of protective serous fluid.","To bind the epithelial cells firmly to the basement membrane."], answer:2 },
  { n:15, section:"Tissues", text:"Gap junctions are heavily concentrated in specific tissue types, like cardiac muscle. What is their primary functional role?", options:["To physically hold cells together so they do not rip apart under extreme tension.","To completely waterproof the space between cells so fluids cannot leak through.","To provide tunnels that allow for the rapid exchange of ions between adjacent cells, synchronizing their electrical activity.","To anchor the basal surface of the cell to the underlying connective tissue.","To package melanin into melanosomes for cellular transport."], answer:2 },
  { n:16, section:"Tissues", text:"Connective tissues serve many structural roles. Which specific functional characteristic allows dense regular connective tissue (found in tendons and ligaments) to resist severe pulling forces in a single direction?", options:["The presence of a massive, fluid-filled synovial cavity.","The random, interwoven meshwork of delicate reticular fibers.","The tightly packed, parallel alignment of thick collagen fibers.","The abundance of large adipocytes acting as shock absorbers.","The completely calcified matrix of hydroxyapatite crystals."], answer:2 },
  { n:17, section:"Tissues", text:"Adipose tissue is a loose connective tissue that functionally serves all of the following physiological roles EXCEPT:", options:["Providing thermal insulation to prevent heat loss.","Acting as a shock-absorbing cushion around vital organs.","Storing systemic energy in the form of triglycerides.","Generating forceful mechanical contractions to move the skeleton.","Filling empty spaces in the hypodermis to anchor the skin."], answer:3 },
  { n:18, section:"Tissues", text:"In nervous tissue, what is the functional difference between dendrites and axons?", options:["Dendrites generate ATP, while axons break down ATP.","Dendrites receive incoming signals from other cells, while axons transmit outgoing electrical signals to target cells.","Dendrites are specialized for contraction, while axons are specialized for elasticity.","Dendrites synthesize myelin, while axons destroy myelin.","Dendrites undergo rapid mitosis, while axons never divide."], answer:1 },
  { n:19, section:"Integumentary", text:"What is the primary protective function of the heavily keratinized, dead cells that make up the stratum corneum of the epidermis?", options:["To actively divide and replace cells lost to daily friction.","To secrete sebum into hair follicles to lubricate the skin.","To provide a tough, waterproof physical barrier that prevents dehydration and resists mechanical abrasion.","To sense deep pressure and intense vibration.","To synthesize massive amounts of active Vitamin D when exposed to the sun."], answer:2 },
  { n:20, section:"Integumentary", text:"Melanocytes produce the pigment melanin in the deep layers of the epidermis. What is the specific functional purpose of this melanin inside the neighboring keratinocytes?", options:["To trap incoming heat and permanently raise the body's core temperature.","To absorb harmful UV radiation and form a protective shield over the cellular DNA to prevent mutations.","To make the skin completely waterproof.","To signal white blood cells to initiate the inflammatory response during an infection.","To break down excess Vitamin D before it reaches toxic levels."], answer:1 },
  { n:21, section:"Integumentary", text:"When you step outside into the hot sun, your eccrine sweat glands secrete watery sweat onto the surface of your skin. Functionally, how does this process cool the body down?", options:["The sweat physically freezes the top layer of the epidermis.","Through the evaporation of the water, which absorbs and draws heat energy away from the skin.","By mixing with sebum to form a reflective barrier against the sun's rays.","By signaling the arrector pili muscles to contract and trap a layer of cool air.","By causing the immediate vasoconstriction of all dermal blood vessels."], answer:1 },
  { n:22, section:"Integumentary", text:"The skin plays a crucial, integrated role in maintaining bone health. Functionally, why is the skin's interaction with UV radiation essential for the skeletal system?", options:["UV radiation directly calcifies the bones of the appendicular skeleton.","UV radiation triggers the skin to synthesize a Vitamin D precursor, which is ultimately required for the intestines to absorb dietary calcium.","UV radiation stimulates the rapid division of osteoclasts to build thicker bone matrix.","UV radiation causes the skin to secrete excess calcium directly onto the bone surface.","UV radiation converts yellow bone marrow directly into red bone marrow."], answer:1 },
  { n:23, section:"Integumentary", text:"If a patient suffers a severe third-degree burn, they often feel no pain in the immediate center of the wound. Functionally, why does this occur?", options:["The intense heat temporarily paralyzes the brain's pain center.","Third-degree burns immediately trigger the massive release of natural endorphins that permanently block all pain.","The burn has completely destroyed the dermis and hypodermis, physically incinerating the sensory nerve endings responsible for pain detection.","The epidermis thickens into a hard callus that blocks pain signals from escaping.","The blood vessels immediately freeze shut to prevent nerve transmission."], answer:2 },
  { n:24, section:"Bones", text:"In the maintenance of bone tissue, what is the functional relationship between osteoblasts and osteoclasts?", options:["Osteoblasts synthesize new cartilage, while osteoclasts turn it into compact bone.","Osteoblasts break down old bone to release calcium, while osteoclasts secrete new bone matrix.","Osteoblasts secrete new bone matrix to build bone, while osteoclasts break down bone matrix to resorb bone.","Osteoblasts produce red blood cells, while osteoclasts produce white blood cells.","Osteoblasts form the periosteum, while osteoclasts form the endosteum."], answer:2 },
  { n:25, section:"Bones", text:"How does the skeletal system functionally respond when the parathyroid glands detect a dangerous drop in blood calcium levels (hypocalcemia)?", options:["Parathyroid hormone (PTH) signals osteoblasts to aggressively deposit calcium into the bones, pulling it out of the blood.","Parathyroid hormone (PTH) stimulates osteoclasts to break down bone matrix, releasing stored calcium into the bloodstream.","Parathyroid hormone (PTH) forces the kidneys to excrete all remaining calcium into the urine.","Parathyroid hormone (PTH) triggers the rapid conversion of compact bone into spongy bone.","Parathyroid hormone (PTH) signals the thyroid gland to release calcitonin."], answer:1 },
  { n:26, section:"Bones", text:"Red bone marrow is a highly active tissue located within the spongy bone. What is its primary physiological function?", options:["Storing systemic energy in the form of dense triglycerides (fat).","Synthesizing the collagen fibers required to build tendons.","Hematopoiesis, which is the continuous production of new red and white blood cells.","Filtering metabolic waste products from the bloodstream.","Generating the electrical impulses required for skeletal muscle contraction."], answer:2 },
  { n:27, section:"Bones", text:"During the process of endochondral ossification in fetal development, what functional role does the hyaline cartilage model serve?", options:["It permanently prevents the bone from ever growing in thickness.","It acts as a temporary structural template that is eventually calcified, hollowed out, and replaced by true bone tissue.","It forms the outer periosteum that protects the bone from infection.","It differentiates directly into red bone marrow.","It converts into dense regular connective tissue to form the nearby ligaments."], answer:1 },
  { n:28, section:"Bones", text:"How do mature osteocytes, trapped deep within the solid, calcified matrix of compact bone, functionally share nutrients and communicate with the central blood supply?", options:["They actively dissolve the matrix around them every day to swim to the central canal.","They rely entirely on anaerobic respiration and do not need a blood supply.","Through microscopic, hair-like channels in the matrix called canaliculi that connect their lacunae together.","By utilizing large perforating canals to migrate out into the periosteum.","By absorbing nutrients directly from the yellow bone marrow in the diaphysis."], answer:2 },
  { n:29, section:"Bones", text:"Wolff's Law states that bones adapt to the physical stresses placed upon them. Functionally, how does bone tissue increase its density in response to a new heavy weightlifting routine?", options:["The mechanical stress forces osteoclasts to undergo rapid apoptosis, preventing any bone from ever breaking down again.","The mechanical stress completely halts all bone remodeling.","The mechanical stress stimulates osteoblasts to secrete additional collagen and calcium phosphate, building a thicker, stronger matrix.","The mechanical stress triggers the medullary cavity to fill solidly with compact bone.","The mechanical stress causes the articular cartilage to convert into compact bone."], answer:2 },
  { n:30, section:"Bones", text:"During the first stage of repairing a severe bone fracture, what is the functional purpose of the initial fracture hematoma (blood clot) that forms?", options:["To instantly fuse the broken bone ends together with a solid block of calcium.","To completely stop the internal bleeding and establish a fibrous framework for the influx of immune and repair cells.","To actively dissolve the remaining healthy bone tissue so the process can start over.","To convert the broken fragments directly into flexible hyaline cartilage.","To permanently seal off the medullary cavity to prevent marrow from escaping."], answer:1 },
  { n:31, section:"Bones", text:"From a functional, biomechanical perspective, why are the diaphyses (shafts) of the long bones in the arms and legs hollowed out to form a medullary cavity rather than being solid blocks of compact bone?", options:["Solid bone would lack the necessary surface area for muscle attachment.","A hollow center maximizes the overall weight of the skeleton, making locomotion much easier.","A hollow tubular design provides immense structural strength against bending forces while keeping the bone lightweight, and creates space to store energy reserves.","The hollow space is required to allow large nerves to pass completely through the limbs.","Solid bone would completely prevent the synthesis of Vitamin D."], answer:2 },
  { n:32, section:"Joints", text:"Synovial fluid is secreted by the synovial membrane into the joint cavity. What are the primary physiological functions of this fluid during joint movement?", options:["To firmly glue the articulating bones together to prevent any unwanted movement.","To provide vital lubrication to reduce friction and to nourish the avascular articular cartilage.","To rapidly synthesize new red blood cells during extreme physical exertion.","To generate the electrical action potentials that signal the muscles to contract.","To dissolve worn-out bone tissue and convert it into fibrous cartilage."], answer:1 },
  { n:33, section:"Joints", text:"Functionally, what is the key biomechanical trade-off of a diarthrosis (a freely movable synovial joint like the shoulder) compared to a synarthrosis (an immobile fibrous joint like a skull suture)?", options:["Diarthroses provide maximum structural stability, but are completely incapable of healing.","Diarthroses allow for a wide range of complex body movements, but their loose attachments make them fundamentally less stable and more prone to dislocation.","Diarthroses use less metabolic energy, but require constant conscious thought to operate.","Diarthroses are highly resistant to arthritis, but easily suffer from osteoporosis.","Diarthroses can only move in a single uniaxial plane, while synarthroses allow multiaxial movement."], answer:1 },
  { n:34, section:"Joints", text:"If a patient experiences a severe \"inversion\" sprain at the ankle during a basketball game, what functional mechanical action has been forced upon the joint?", options:["The top of the foot has been forcefully bent upward toward the shin.","The bottom of the foot has been forcefully turned inward toward the body's midline, overstretching the lateral ligaments.","The bottom of the foot has been forcefully turned outward away from the body's midline.","The foot has been perfectly rotated 360 degrees around the tibia.","The toes have been forcefully pointed downward in extreme plantar flexion."], answer:1 },
  { n:35, section:"Joints", text:"What is the specific functional role of a bursa located near a highly mobile synovial joint (such as the subacromial bursa in the shoulder)?", options:["To act as an aggressive immune gland that constantly filters the synovial fluid.","To directly anchor the muscle belly to the bone surface.","To act as a fluid-filled cushion that prevents frictional wear-and-tear where tendons, ligaments, or skin rub against the underlying bone.","To physically lock the joint in place during sleep.","To secrete the calcium necessary to harden the articular cartilage."], answer:2 },
  { n:36, section:"Muscles", text:"Excitability is a core characteristic of skeletal muscle cells. Functionally, what does this specific property enable the muscle fiber to do?", options:["It enables the muscle fiber to actively pull on the bone with immense force.","It enables the muscle fiber to passively stretch beyond its normal resting length without tearing.","It enables the muscle fiber to receive and respond to electrical or chemical signals from a motor neuron.","It enables the muscle fiber to recoil like a rubber band back to its original shape.","It enables the muscle fiber to undergo rapid mitosis to heal injuries."], answer:2 },
  { n:37, section:"Muscles", text:"During the initiation of a muscle contraction, what is the specific functional role of the calcium ions (Ca2+) released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum?", options:["They bind directly to the myosin heads to provide the energy for the power stroke.","They bind to troponin, causing a shape change that pulls tropomyosin away, thereby exposing the active myosin-binding sites on the actin filament.","They physically push the Z-discs closer together to shorten the sarcomere.","They travel back up the motor neuron to signal that the contraction has started.","They convert lactic acid back into functional glucose."], answer:1 },
  { n:38, section:"Muscles", text:"What highly specific functional role does ATP play during the cross-bridge cycling (\"Power Stroke\") of a muscle contraction?", options:["It blocks the active binding sites on actin when the muscle needs to relax.","It triggers the initial release of calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","Its hydrolysis provides the energy to \"cock\" the myosin head into the ready position, and the binding of a new ATP allows the myosin head to successfully detach from actin.","It anchors the thick filaments to the Z-disc to prevent the sarcomere from overstretching.","It physically forces the sodium-potassium pumps to shut down during the contraction."], answer:2 },
  { n:39, section:"Muscles", text:"In a resting, relaxed muscle fiber, what is the functional purpose of the regulatory protein tropomyosin?", options:["It physically blocks the active binding sites on the actin filament, preventing the myosin heads from attaching and causing an involuntary contraction.","It acts as a calcium-storage reservoir in the sarcoplasm.","It binds directly to ATP to synthesize massive amounts of metabolic energy.","It forms the thick filament that pulls on the Z-discs.","It rapidly pumps sodium out of the cell to maintain the resting membrane potential."], answer:0 },
  { n:40, section:"Muscles", text:"Muscle cells generate massive amounts of metabolic heat as a byproduct of contraction. In the context of total body homeostasis, how is this heat production utilized functionally?", options:["It is used to intentionally denature proteins to fight off severe viral infections.","It is triggered via involuntary shivering to raise the core body temperature when it falls below the normal homeostatic set-point.","It is used to actively boil away excess water inside the stomach during digestion.","It is transferred to the bones to help melt and reshape the hydroxyapatite crystals.","It is utilized solely to speed up the transmission of action potentials in the brain."], answer:1 },
  { n:41, section:"Muscles", text:"T-tubules are deep, tunnel-like invaginations of the muscle cell membrane (sarcolemma). What is their critical physiological function during excitation?", options:["To act as a physical drain for excess lactic acid to leave the muscle fiber.","To rapidly conduct the electrical action potential deep into the interior of the cell, ensuring all parts of the sarcoplasmic reticulum release calcium simultaneously.","To store extra oxygen for the mitochondria to use during heavy exercise.","To anchor the muscle fiber directly to the overlying endomysium.","To transport massive bundles of newly synthesized proteins out of the cell."], answer:1 },
  { n:42, section:"Muscles", text:"From a functional energy standpoint, what is the primary purpose of creatine phosphate in a muscle cell during the first 10 to 15 seconds of an all-out, intense sprint?", options:["It acts as a long-term storage molecule for vast amounts of oxygen.","It permanently prevents the formation of lactic acid.","It rapidly donates a phosphate group directly to ADP, instantly regenerating ATP without requiring the use of oxygen.","It slowly breaks down triglycerides to fuel hours of endurance running.","It physically binds the myosin head to the actin filament in the absence of calcium."], answer:2 },
  { n:43, section:"Muscles", text:"When you lift a heavy textbook from a desk up toward your shoulder, your biceps brachii muscle actively generates force while visibly shortening in length. What functional type of muscle contraction is this?", options:["Isometric contraction","Isotonic eccentric contraction","Isotonic concentric contraction","Tetanic contraction","Flaccid paralysis"], answer:2 },
  { n:44, section:"Muscles", text:"What is the functional physiological significance of motor units containing vastly different numbers of muscle fibers (e.g., an eye muscle having 5 fibers per neuron vs. a calf muscle having 1,000 fibers per neuron)?", options:["It determines whether a muscle will use aerobic or anaerobic respiration.","Small motor units allow the nervous system to execute precise, delicate movements, while large motor units allow for massive, powerful movements.","Small motor units generate more heat, while large motor units generate less heat.","It prevents the muscles from ever running out of ATP.","It ensures that all muscles contract at the exact same speed regardless of their location."], answer:1 },
  { n:45, section:"Muscles", text:"Smooth muscle surrounds many hollow organs, including the walls of the digestive tract. What is a primary functional role of smooth muscle in these locations?", options:["To perform extremely rapid, voluntary contractions to digest food instantly.","To continuously generate red blood cells for the nearby organs.","To perform slow, involuntary, rhythmic contractions (peristalsis) that systematically propel substances through the body.","To physically grind solid food into liquid using rigid protein fibers.","To maintain a perfectly rigid, immobile posture for the abdominal cavity."], answer:2 },
  { n:46, section:"Muscles", text:"In cardiac muscle tissue, what is the specific functional purpose of the desmosomes located within the intercalated discs?", options:["To electrically insulate the cells so they act completely independently of one another.","To mechanically anchor the adjacent cells tightly together so they do not rip apart under the intense pressure of a heartbeat.","To synthesize the massive amounts of ATP required for continuous beating.","To prevent calcium from ever entering the cardiac muscle fiber.","To automatically repair any damage done to the heart valves."], answer:1 },
  { n:47, section:"Muscles", text:"Slow oxidative (SO) muscle fibers are heavily concentrated in the postural muscles of the back and neck. Functionally, why is this specific fiber type ideal for maintaining posture?", options:["They rely strictly on anaerobic glycolysis and produce massive, explosive power for a few seconds.","They completely lack myoglobin, making them lighter and easier to contract.","They rapidly deplete their ATP stores, allowing the muscles to rest frequently.","They rely heavily on aerobic respiration, have massive blood supplies, and are highly resistant to fatigue, allowing for continuous, low-level tension over long periods.","They can only be activated by conscious, intense voluntary effort."], answer:3 },
  { n:48, section:"Muscles", text:"A \"synergist\" muscle works in tandem with a prime mover (agonist). What is the functional biomechanical benefit of a synergist during a complex movement?", options:["It perfectly opposes the action of the prime mover to stop the joint from moving entirely.","It acts strictly to reverse the movement once the prime mover is finished.","It helps stabilize the joint or adds extra force in the same direction to ensure the prime mover acts efficiently and smoothly.","It secretes extra synovial fluid to lubricate the joint during the movement.","It cuts off the blood supply to the antagonist muscle."], answer:2 },
  { n:49, section:"Muscles", text:"During highly rigorous, exhausting exercise, a muscle may temporarily outpace its oxygen supply. How does the muscle functionally continue to produce ATP for a short time under these conditions?", options:["By switching to anaerobic glycolysis, which rapidly breaks down glucose to produce ATP without oxygen, generating lactic acid as a byproduct.","By immediately digesting its own actin and myosin proteins.","By pulling extra oxygen directly from the surrounding skin cells.","By halting all contractions until the lungs can catch up.","By utilizing the electron transport chain at double the normal speed."], answer:0 },
  { n:50, section:"Nervous System", text:"During the rapid depolarization phase of an action potential in an excitable muscle or nerve cell, what is functionally occurring across the cell membrane to initiate the signal?", options:["Positively charged potassium ions (K+) rapidly exit the cell, restoring the negative resting charge.","Negatively charged chloride ions (Cl-) rapidly enter the cell, making it intensely negative.","Massive amounts of ATP are pumped out of the cell into the interstitial fluid.","Positively charged sodium ions (Na+) rapidly rush into the cell, dramatically reducing the negative electrical charge inside the membrane.","The cell physically secretes all of its neurotransmitters at once."], answer:3 },

  // ---- Section 2: Applied Physiology of the Musculoskeletal System (Q51–100) ----
  { n:51, section:"Bones", text:"According to Wolff's Law, bones adapt structurally to the mechanical loads placed upon them. Functionally, how does the bone tissue achieve an increase in density and strength when a person engages in heavy resistance training?", options:["The mechanical stress forces the yellow bone marrow to convert into solid calcium carbonate.","The mechanical stress directly inhibits all osteoclast activity, preventing any bone tissue from ever being broken down again.","The mechanical stress stimulates osteoblasts to secrete additional uncalcified osteoid (collagen) and deposit more hydroxyapatite crystals, building a thicker matrix.","The mechanical stress triggers the rapid division of osteocytes within their lacunae.","The mechanical stress causes the articular cartilage to ossify into compact bone."], answer:2 },
  { n:52, section:"Bones", text:"In a patient with Crohn's disease, chronic inflammation severely damages the intestinal lining, reducing the absorption of dietary nutrients. Functionally, how will this disease affect the patient's calcium homeostasis feedback loop?", options:["The resulting hypocalcemia will trigger the parathyroid glands to increase the production of Parathyroid Hormone (PTH), stimulating osteoclasts to break down bone matrix to release calcium into the blood.","The resulting hypercalcemia will trigger the thyroid gland to release calcitonin, which stimulates osteoblasts to build new bone.","The parathyroid glands will shut down completely to conserve whatever calcium remains in the bloodstream.","The kidneys will automatically synthesize new calcium atoms to replace the ones lost in the digestive tract.","The body will permanently convert all its yellow bone marrow into red bone marrow to absorb calcium directly from the air."], answer:0 },
  { n:53, section:"Joints", text:"In a freely movable diarthrosis like the knee, what is the primary physiological function of the synovial fluid secreted by the synovial membrane?", options:["To act as a solid, immovable biological glue that holds the femur and tibia together.","To generate electrical action potentials that signal the surrounding skeletal muscles to contract.","To provide vital lubrication to reduce friction and to act as the sole source of metabolic nourishment for the avascular articular cartilage.","To rapidly synthesize new red blood cells during extreme physical exertion.","To dissolve worn-out compact bone tissue and convert it into fibrous cartilage."], answer:2 },
  { n:54, section:"Joints", text:"Functionally, what is the key biomechanical trade-off inherent to all highly mobile synovial joints (like the glenohumeral joint of the shoulder) compared to immobile fibrous joints (like the sutures of the skull)?", options:["Highly mobile joints use less metabolic ATP but require constant conscious thought to operate.","Highly mobile joints allow for a wide range of complex body movements, but their loose structural attachments make them fundamentally less stable and much more prone to dislocation.","Highly mobile joints are completely immune to osteoarthritis, but easily suffer from osteoporosis.","Highly mobile joints can only move in a single uniaxial plane, while immobile joints allow for multiaxial rotation.","Highly mobile joints rely entirely on anaerobic respiration, while immobile joints rely strictly on aerobic respiration."], answer:1 },
  { n:55, section:"Joints", text:"A patient suffers a severe \"inversion\" sprain while running on an uneven trail. Functionally, what specific structural damage defines a sprain?", options:["The severe stretching or tearing of a tendon that anchors a muscle to a bone.","The severe stretching or tearing of a ligament, which is the dense connective tissue that stabilizes the joint by connecting bone to bone.","The complete shattering of the articular cartilage into the synovial cavity.","The inflammation of a fluid-filled bursa due to repetitive friction.","The surgical removal of a meniscus from the knee capsule."], answer:1 },
  { n:56, section:"Joints", text:"Osteoarthritis is a common joint disorder in older adults. Functionally, what physiological process is primarily responsible for the symptoms of osteoarthritis?", options:["An autoimmune response where the body's white blood cells aggressively attack and destroy the healthy synovial membrane.","A severe bacterial infection that invades the medullary cavity of the long bones.","The aging and physical \"wear-and-tear\" erosion of the protective articular cartilage, leading to increased pressure, bone thickening, and painful bone-on-bone friction.","The overproduction of synovial fluid, which causes the joint capsule to spontaneously burst.","The conversion of dense regular connective tissue ligaments into fragile elastic cartilage."], answer:2 },
  { n:57, section:"Joints", text:"What is the specific functional role of a bursa located near a highly active synovial joint?", options:["To act as a powerful immune gland that filters bacteria out of the synovial fluid.","To serve as an elongated sheath that securely anchors a muscle belly directly to the bone surface.","To act as a fluid-filled cushion that reduces mechanical friction where skin, ligaments, muscles, or tendons rub tightly against the underlying bone.","To physically lock the joint in place to prevent movement during sleep.","To secrete the hydroxyapatite crystals necessary to harden the articular cartilage."], answer:2 },
  { n:58, section:"Joints", text:"If a patient severely ruptures a tendon (a strain), their recovery time will be significantly longer than if they had suffered a clean bone fracture. Functionally, why do tendons heal at such a slow rate?", options:["Tendons are composed of dead keratinocytes that physically cannot undergo mitosis.","Tendons lack collagen fibers, making it impossible to form a protective scar.","Tendons are composed of dense regular connective tissue, which is highly avascular and lacks the strong blood supply needed to deliver repair cells and nutrients quickly.","Tendons are constantly bathed in acidic synovial fluid that actively prevents collagen synthesis.","Tendons rely strictly on gap junctions to transmit healing factors across the body."], answer:2 },
  { n:59, section:"Muscles", text:"During the complex process of muscle contraction, what specific functional role do the T-tubules serve in the excitation-contraction coupling phase?", options:["They act as physical drains to rapidly flush excess lactic acid out of the muscle fiber.","They rapidly conduct the electrical action potential from the sarcolemma deep into the interior of the cell, ensuring the entire sarcoplasmic reticulum releases calcium simultaneously.","They store massive reserves of oxygen for the mitochondria to use during extreme aerobic exercise.","They anchor the deep muscle fibers directly to the overlying dense connective tissue of the epimysium.","They pump positively charged sodium ions out of the cell to restore the resting membrane potential."], answer:1 },
  { n:60, section:"Muscles", text:"The sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR) is a highly specialized organelle in muscle fibers. What is its primary physiological function?", options:["To synthesize the massive amounts of ATP required for cross-bridge cycling.","To digest old, worn-out contractile proteins using acid hydrolases.","To act as a dedicated intracellular reservoir that actively stores, retrieves, and releases the calcium ions (Ca2+) necessary to trigger a contraction.","To package newly made actin and myosin proteins into vesicles for exocytosis.","To physically link the Z-discs of adjacent sarcomeres together."], answer:2 },
  { n:61, section:"Muscles", text:"In a resting muscle fiber, the regulatory protein tropomyosin plays a critical functional role. What does it do?", options:["It acts as an elastic spring that pushes the Z-discs apart, keeping the muscle elongated.","It physically covers and blocks the active myosin-binding sites on the actin filament, preventing the myosin heads from attaching and causing an unwanted contraction.","It binds directly to free ATP molecules to synthesize vast amounts of metabolic energy.","It acts as an intracellular calcium sponge, sucking up free ions from the sarcoplasm.","It rapidly pumps sodium out of the cell to maintain the resting membrane potential."], answer:1 },
  { n:62, section:"Muscles", text:"When an action potential triggers the release of calcium into the sarcoplasm, what is the immediate physiological consequence of that calcium binding to the regulatory protein troponin?", options:["Troponin instantly undergoes a shape change that pulls tropomyosin away, thereby exposing the active binding sites on the actin filament and allowing the myosin head to attach.","Troponin binds directly to the myosin head, providing the raw energy needed for the power stroke.","Troponin physically pushes the Z-discs closer together to shorten the sarcomere.","Troponin rapidly converts any accumulated lactic acid back into functional glucose.","Troponin breaks down ATP into ADP and an inorganic phosphate."], answer:0 },
  { n:63, section:"Muscles", text:"During the \"Power Stroke\" phase of cross-bridge cycling, the myosin head pivots, pulling the actin filament toward the center of the sarcomere. What specific chemical event triggers this physical pivoting motion?", options:["The sudden influx of sodium into the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","The release of ADP and inorganic phosphate (Pi) from the myosin head after it successfully binds to actin.","The binding of a fresh, intact ATP molecule directly to the actin filament.","The destruction of the structural M-line proteins.","The sudden release of oxygen from myoglobin stores."], answer:1 },
  { n:64, section:"Muscles", text:"In order for the myosin head to successfully DETACH from the actin filament after completing a power stroke, what functional chemical step must occur?", options:["A new molecule of ATP must physically bind to the ATP-binding site on the myosin head.","Calcium must forcefully detach from the troponin complex.","The muscle cell must completely exhaust its intracellular oxygen supply.","The myosin head must rapidly reabsorb the ADP and Pi it just released.","A new action potential must fire from the motor neuron."], answer:0 },
  { n:65, section:"Muscles", text:"If a person dies and their cells completely stop synthesizing ATP, their muscles will eventually become permanently locked in a rigid state known as rigor mortis. Functionally, why does this happen?", options:["The actin and myosin filaments immediately dissolve into the bloodstream.","Without ATP to bind to the myosin heads, the cross-bridges cannot detach from the actin filaments, leaving the muscles permanently contracted.","Tropomyosin permanently fuses to the active sites on actin, creating a solid bone-like matrix.","The sarcoplasmic reticulum rapidly absorbs all the structural proteins of the sarcomere.","Titin actively expands, violently pushing the Z-discs apart until the muscle freezes."], answer:1 },
  { n:66, section:"Muscles", text:"Muscle cells require massive, immediate supplies of ATP to fuel an intense sprint. From a functional energy standpoint, what is the primary purpose of creatine phosphate during the first 10 to 15 seconds of intense exercise?", options:["It acts as a long-term storage molecule for excess oxygen, replacing myoglobin.","It permanently blocks the formation of lactic acid in the muscle tissue.","It rapidly donates a high-energy phosphate group directly to ADP, instantly regenerating ATP without requiring the use of oxygen.","It breaks down large triglyceride chains to fuel hours of slow, aerobic endurance running.","It physically binds the myosin head to the actin filament when calcium is completely depleted."], answer:2 },
  { n:67, section:"Muscles", text:"During highly rigorous, exhausting exercise, a muscle may temporarily outpace its cardiovascular oxygen supply. How does the muscle functionally continue to produce ATP for a short burst of time under these anaerobic conditions?", options:["By utilizing the electron transport chain at quadruple the normal physiological speed.","By switching entirely to anaerobic glycolysis, which rapidly breaks down glucose to produce 2 net ATP per cycle without oxygen, generating lactic acid as a fatiguing byproduct.","By instantly digesting its own structural actin and myosin proteins to harvest their energy.","By halting all sliding filament contractions until the lungs can catch up.","By pulling extra oxygen directly through the skin from the surrounding atmosphere."], answer:1 },
  { n:68, section:"Muscles", text:"Slow oxidative (SO) muscle fibers are heavily concentrated in the postural muscles of the human back. Functionally, why is this specific fiber type perfectly adapted for maintaining upright posture?", options:["They rely strictly on anaerobic glycolysis, producing massive, explosive power for just a few seconds before complete failure.","They completely lack myoglobin and mitochondria, making them physically lighter and easier to contract against gravity.","They rapidly deplete their internal ATP stores, allowing the postural muscles to rest frequently and prevent spine damage.","They rely heavily on aerobic respiration, have massive blood supplies, and are highly resistant to fatigue, allowing them to sustain low-level tension for hours.","They can only be activated by conscious, intense, voluntary neurological effort."], answer:3 },
  { n:69, section:"Muscles", text:"What is the functional physiological significance of motor units containing vastly different numbers of muscle fibers (e.g., an extraocular eye muscle having 5 fibers per neuron vs. a gastrocnemius calf muscle having 1,000 fibers per neuron)?", options:["It determines whether a muscle will use primarily aerobic or anaerobic respiration pathways.","Small motor units allow the nervous system to execute precise, delicate, highly coordinated movements, while large motor units allow the nervous system to execute massive, powerful, gross movements.","Small motor units generate excessive metabolic heat, while large motor units generate almost no heat.","It prevents the smaller muscles from ever running out of ATP during heavy exercise.","It ensures that all muscles contract at the exact same physical speed regardless of their anatomical location."], answer:1 },
  { n:70, section:"Muscles", text:"When you slowly and carefully lower a heavy box from a shelf down to the floor, your biceps brachii muscle is maintaining high tension while gradually lengthening. This is an example of what functional type of muscle contraction?", options:["A concentric isotonic contraction.","An eccentric isotonic contraction.","An isometric contraction.","A tetanic wave summation.","Flaccid muscular paralysis."], answer:1 },
  { n:71, section:"Muscles", text:"In cardiac muscle tissue, what is the specific functional purpose of the gap junctions located within the intercalated discs?", options:["To completely electrically insulate the heart cells so they act totally independently of one another.","To mechanically anchor the adjacent cells tightly together so they do not rip apart under the intense pressure of a heartbeat.","To provide open ion channels that allow depolarizing electrical currents to spread rapidly from one cardiac cell directly to the next, ensuring the heart contracts as a synchronized unit.","To prevent toxic extracellular calcium from ever entering the sensitive cardiac muscle fiber.","To automatically secrete lubricating fluid to repair any frictional damage done to the heart valves."], answer:2 },
  { n:72, section:"Muscles", text:"Smooth muscle surrounds many hollow organs, including the walls of the intestines. What is a primary functional role of smooth muscle in these digestive locations?", options:["To perform extremely rapid, powerful, voluntary contractions to digest food instantly.","To continuously generate red blood cells to supply the nearby digestive glands.","To perform slow, involuntary, rhythmic, wave-like contractions (peristalsis) that systematically propel substances through the body tract.","To physically grind hard, solid food into liquid using rigid intracellular protein networks.","To maintain a perfectly rigid, immobile postural framework for the abdominal cavity."], answer:2 },
  { n:73, section:"Muscles", text:"The process of significantly increasing the physical size and mass of a muscle through rigorous exercise (like weightlifting) is called hypertrophy. Functionally, how is this achieved at the cellular level?", options:["By stimulating the mature muscle fibers to rapidly undergo mitosis and divide into thousands of new cells.","By adding more fluid and fat inside the medullary cavities of the surrounding bones.","By stimulating the existing muscle fibers to synthesize and add new structural proteins (more actin and myosin filaments), thereby increasing the diameter of the cells.","By permanently stretching the elastic titin proteins so the resting muscle length is doubled.","By increasing the total amount of lactic acid permanently stored in the sarcoplasm."], answer:2 },
  { n:74, section:"Muscles", text:"The \"prime mover\" (or agonist) is the principal muscle responsible for producing a specific movement at a joint. What is the functional biomechanical role of a \"synergist\" muscle during that same movement?", options:["It perfectly opposes the action of the prime mover to act as a biological brake and stop the joint from moving entirely.","It acts strictly to reverse the movement once the prime mover is finished.","It assists the prime mover by adding extra force in the same direction or by stabilizing the joint to ensure the movement is smooth and efficient.","It secretes extra synovial fluid to rapidly lubricate the joint during the intense movement.","It intentionally cuts off the blood supply to the antagonist muscle to weaken it."], answer:2 },
  { n:75, section:"Muscles", text:"What is the specific functional purpose of the structural protein titin within a sarcomere?", options:["It acts as a rigid, unbending rod that prevents the muscle from ever changing its resting length.","It serves as the primary binding site for calcium ions to initiate the sliding filament mechanism.","It acts as a massive, elastic spring that anchors the thick myosin filaments laterally to the Z-discs, allowing the muscle to recoil after being stretched and preventing overstretching.","It chemically breaks down ATP molecules into ADP and inorganic phosphate.","It wraps entirely around the exterior of the muscle fascicle to form the perimysium."], answer:2 },
  { n:76, section:"Nervous System", text:"During an action potential in an excitable nerve or muscle cell membrane, what specific functional event characterizes the rapid depolarization phase?", options:["Positively charged potassium ions (K+) rapidly exit the cell through voltage-gated channels, restoring the negative resting charge.","Massive amounts of negatively charged chloride ions (Cl-) rapidly enter the cell, making the interior intensely negative.","Positively charged sodium ions (Na+) rapidly rush into the cell through open channels, dramatically reducing the negative electrical charge inside the membrane and pushing the voltage toward zero or higher.","The cell physically secretes all of its stored intracellular neurotransmitters at once.","The sodium-potassium pump permanently shuts down to conserve massive amounts of ATP."], answer:2 },
  { n:77, section:"Nervous System", text:"The nervous system utilizes different types of gated ion channels to trigger signals. Functionally, what specific event is required to open a \"ligand-gated\" channel?", options:["A significant physical deformation or stretching of the cell membrane.","A drastic change in the electrical voltage across the local membrane.","The binding of a specific chemical messenger (a neurotransmitter, like acetylcholine) to a receptor site on the channel protein.","The complete exhaustion of the cell's intracellular ATP supply.","An extreme drop in the environmental temperature."], answer:2 },
  { n:78, section:"Nervous System", text:"In contrast, \"mechanically gated\" ion channels are heavily utilized in the sensory receptors of the integumentary system. Functionally, what event causes these specific channels to open?", options:["The binding of a chemical neurotransmitter released from a neighboring cell.","A physical stimulus, such as pressure, vibration, or tactile touch, that physically deforms the structure of the channel protein.","The membrane voltage becoming significantly less negative.","The rapid accumulation of carbon dioxide in the extracellular fluid.","The sudden release of calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum."], answer:1 },
  { n:79, section:"Nervous System", text:"The autonomic nervous system regulates involuntary physiological processes. When the sympathetic division triggers the \"fight-or-flight\" response, what functional change occurs in the cardiovascular system to prepare the body for extreme action?", options:["It triggers massive systemic vasodilation, dropping blood pressure to zero to prevent bleeding from potential wounds.","It completely shuts down the heart rate so the body can \"play dead\" to avoid predators.","It stimulates the release of epinephrine, increasing the heart rate and redirecting (shunting) blood flow away from the digestive tract and toward the critical skeletal muscles.","It forces the kidneys to excrete all remaining water to make the body lighter for running.","It aggressively constricts the airways in the lungs to prevent the inhalation of toxic environmental dust."], answer:2 },
  { n:80, section:"Nervous System", text:"Myelin sheaths functionally insulate the axons of many neurons in the nervous system. What is the primary physiological benefit of this myelination?", options:["It drastically slows down the speed of an action potential to ensure the brain has time to process the signal.","It significantly increases the speed at which electrical action potentials propagate (travel) down the length of the axon.","It completely prevents the axon from ever firing an action potential.","It allows the neuron to perform massive amounts of phagocytosis.","It converts the neuron's electrical signals into physical muscle contractions without the need for a synapse."], answer:1 },
  { n:81, section:"Nervous System", text:"During a neurological exam, the \"Romberg test\" asks a patient to stand completely still and upright with their eyes closed. Functionally, what specific physiological sense is this test primarily evaluating if the patient suddenly loses their balance?", options:["The functional integrity of their visual tracking and extraocular eye muscles.","The functional integrity of their proprioception—the unconscious sensory perception of joint and limb positioning without visual feedback.","The functional integrity of their primary motor cortex to initiate conscious movement.","The functional integrity of their pain and temperature sensory pathways.","The functional integrity of their olfactory (smell) and gustatory (taste) receptors."], answer:1 },
  { n:82, section:"Bones", text:"The skeletal system is described as a massive reservoir for calcium and phosphate. Functionally, why is it absolutely critical for the body to maintain tight homeostatic control over free serum calcium levels in the blood?", options:["Calcium is the only mineral capable of transporting oxygen through the bloodstream to the brain.","Calcium is highly toxic and must be actively locked away in the bone matrix to prevent immediate cell death.","Free calcium ions are functionally required for initiating muscle contractions, nerve impulse transmission, and the blood clotting cascade.","Free calcium ions are the primary source of metabolic calories used to synthesize ATP.","Calcium is solely responsible for generating the tough, waterproof keratin layer of the epidermis."], answer:2 },
  { n:83, section:"Bones", text:"Following a severe bone fracture, the body initiates a four-step repair process. During the \"Remodeling\" phase (the final stage), what functional change occurs to the newly formed bone tissue?", options:["The body forms a massive, uncontrolled blood clot to permanently seal off the medullary cavity.","Osteoblasts rapidly lay down an unorganized, chaotic matrix of woven hyaline cartilage.","Osteoclasts and osteoblasts work together to slowly replace the bulky, temporary spongy bone of the hard callus with highly organized, structurally superior compact bone.","The entire bone dissolves into the bloodstream and regenerates completely from scratch.","The periosteum is permanently stripped away from the fracture site."], answer:2 },
  { n:84, section:"Bones", text:"Why does an \"open\" (compound) bone fracture carry a significantly higher clinical risk of severe complications compared to a \"closed\" (simple) fracture?", options:["An open fracture means the bone has bent but not actually broken completely, making it impossible to set in a cast.","An open fracture means the broken ends of the bone have physically pierced through the protective barrier of the skin, exposing the deep tissues and bone marrow to high risks of external bacterial infection.","An open fracture means the bone has shattered into dozens of microscopic, comminuted pieces.","An open fracture forces the body to rely entirely on intramembranous ossification for repair.","An open fracture permanently paralyzes all nearby skeletal muscles."], answer:1 },
  { n:85, section:"Bones", text:"When identifying a tissue slide under a microscope, you observe tightly packed osteons with distinct central canals and concentric lamellae, but absolutely no open trabecular spaces. Functionally, what is the primary role of this specific type of tissue?", options:["To provide a lightweight, shock-absorbing framework that houses red bone marrow for hematopoiesis.","To form the dense, incredibly strong exterior layer of bones that provides rigid support and protection against compressive forces.","To provide a smooth, low-friction, avascular surface for joints to articulate against.","To rapidly transmit electrical action potentials down the length of the spinal cord.","To expand and stretch rapidly to accommodate the filling of the urinary bladder."], answer:1 },
  { n:86, section:"Joints", text:"A syndesmosis is a fibrous joint where two parallel bones are united by a wide sheet of connective tissue (like the interosseous membrane between the radius and ulna). Functionally, what is the advantage of this specific joint structure?", options:["It allows for 360-degree, multiaxial rotation of the two bones around each other.","It completely paralyzes the limb to ensure perfectly rigid stability during walking.","It firmly binds the bones together to prevent them from separating, while still allowing for a slight, functional amount of give or rotation (amphiarthrosis).","It secretes vast amounts of synovial fluid to permanently lubricate the deep muscle bellies.","It forces the two bones to eventually fuse together into a solid synostosis during puberty."], answer:2 },
  { n:87, section:"Muscles", text:"Functionally, what occurs when a skeletal muscle performs an \"isometric\" contraction?", options:["The muscle violently spasms due to a complete lack of intracellular ATP.","The muscle generates high tension and actively shortens in length to successfully move a heavy load.","The muscle generates high tension while actively lengthening to slowly resist a heavy load.","The muscle generates immense tension, but the load is too heavy to move, so the muscle's physical length does not visibly change.","The muscle completely relaxes and flaccidly drops the load."], answer:3 },
  { n:88, section:"Muscles", text:"What is the functional role of the \"fixator\" muscle during a complex biomechanical movement?", options:["It acts as the primary source of pulling force to execute the desired joint movement.","It strictly opposes the movement to ensure the joint does not overextend and dislocate.","It stabilizes the origin bone of the prime mover, ensuring that all the generated tension is efficiently directed toward pulling on the insertion bone.","It secretes the necessary neurotransmitters to initiate the contraction at the neuromuscular junction.","It rapidly pumps calcium back into the sarcoplasmic reticulum to end the contraction."], answer:2 },
  { n:89, section:"Muscles", text:"Muscles rely on the precise timing of action potentials. If rapid, successive electrical stimuli arrive at a muscle fiber before it has completely relaxed from the previous stimulus, the muscle twitches will chemically add together to produce a significantly stronger overall contraction. Functionally, what is this phenomenon called?", options:["Atrophy.","Treppe.","Flaccid paralysis.","Rigor mortis.","Wave summation."], answer:4 },
  { n:90, section:"Muscles", text:"The nervous system controls muscle contraction strength by \"recruiting\" motor units. Functionally, how does the body smoothly increase the amount of force a muscle generates when lifting a progressively heavier object?", options:["By intentionally breaking down the protective perimysium to allow the muscle to swell.","By signaling all motor units to fire simultaneously at maximum power for every single movement, regardless of weight.","By initially activating small, precise motor units, and then progressively recruiting larger, more powerful motor units as more force is required.","By permanently converting all slow oxidative fibers into fast glycolytic fibers.","By actively flooding the entire muscle belly with acidic lactic acid to stimulate pain receptors."], answer:2 },
  { n:91, section:"Muscles", text:"At the neuromuscular junction, the motor neuron releases the neurotransmitter acetylcholine (ACh) into the synaptic cleft. Functionally, what is the immediate effect of ACh binding to the receptors on the muscle cell's sarcolemma?", options:["It opens ligand-gated ion channels, allowing a massive influx of sodium (Na+) that initiates the depolarizing action potential on the muscle membrane.","It triggers the immediate, forceful detachment of the myosin head from the actin filament.","It causes the muscle cell to rapidly undergo mitosis to build more muscle mass.","It physically blocks the release of calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.","It converts ADP back into functional ATP."], answer:0 },
  { n:92, section:"Muscles", text:"Myoglobin is an iron-rich protein heavily concentrated in certain muscle tissues. What is its primary physiological function?", options:["To act as a rigid structural beam that holds the Z-discs together.","To actively store and transport oxygen within the sarcoplasm, ensuring a ready supply for aerobic respiration during sustained muscle activity.","To rapidly synthesize new molecules of glucose from lactic acid.","To permanently block the binding sites on the actin filament when the muscle is at rest.","To generate the thick, dark pigment required to protect the muscle from UV radiation damage."], answer:1 },
  { n:93, section:"Nervous System", text:"What is the functional difference between an \"afferent\" nervous pathway and an \"efferent\" nervous pathway?", options:["Afferent pathways generate ATP; efferent pathways consume ATP.","Afferent pathways conduct sensory information from the body toward the central nervous system; efferent pathways conduct motor commands away from the central nervous system out to the muscles and glands.","Afferent pathways control voluntary skeletal muscles; efferent pathways strictly control involuntary smooth muscle.","Afferent pathways utilize only chemical neurotransmitters; efferent pathways utilize only direct electrical gap junctions.","Afferent pathways are strictly found in the brain; efferent pathways are strictly found in the spinal cord."], answer:1 },
  { n:94, section:"Nervous System", text:"Epinephrine (adrenaline) is released from the adrenal medulla into the bloodstream during sympathetic activation. Functionally, how does this circulating hormone assist skeletal muscles during a sudden emergency?", options:["It forces the skeletal muscles to completely relax and conserve their energy reserves.","It causes severe systemic vasoconstriction that cuts off all blood flow to the limbs.","It increases the heart rate and causes vasodilation of the blood vessels supplying the skeletal muscles, delivering a massive surge of oxygen and glucose for explosive movement.","It chemically triggers the immediate apoptosis of all damaged muscle fibers.","It converts the muscle's stored glycogen directly into rigid bone tissue for protection."], answer:2 },
  { n:95, section:"Nervous System", text:"A patient has a condition that selectively destroys the myelin sheaths of their somatic motor neurons (such as in certain demyelinating diseases). Functionally, what will be the primary consequence of this destruction?", options:["Their muscles will undergo massive, uncontrolled hypertrophy and double in size.","Their motor action potentials will travel significantly slower, leading to delayed, weak, or uncoordinated voluntary muscle contractions (paresis).","Their sensory receptors will become hyper-sensitive to light touch and temperature.","Their bones will rapidly lose calcium and become severely osteoporotic.","Their smooth muscle digestive tracts will begin moving at quadruple the normal speed."], answer:1 },
  { n:96, section:"Nervous System", text:"A stroke in the primary motor cortex of the frontal lobe often leads to paralysis on the opposite side of the body. Functionally, why does damage to the brain cause the muscles to fail to contract?", options:["The brain is the only organ capable of synthesizing the ATP required by the muscles.","The stroke physically travels through the bloodstream to poison the muscle fibers directly.","The primary motor cortex houses the upper motor neurons that generate the conscious electrical commands; without this initial signal, the lower motor neurons are never triggered to release acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction.","The brain is responsible for secreting all the calcium necessary for cross-bridge cycling.","The stroke causes the skeletal muscles to permanently convert into smooth muscle."], answer:2 },
  { n:97, section:"Nervous System", text:"Sensory transduction is a key physiological process. When a sound wave hits the inner ear, hair cells bend. Functionally, what must happen next for the brain to perceive this physical sound?", options:["The hair cells must actively swim up the auditory nerve into the temporal lobe.","The physical bending of the hair cells must mechanically open ion channels, converting the mechanical stimulus into an electrical action potential (transduction) that can travel to the brain.","The sound wave must physically travel through the bloodstream until it vibrates the skull bones.","The hair cells must release massive amounts of acidic fluid to dissolve the tympanic membrane.","The brain must send a motor signal backward to the ear to ask what the sound was."], answer:1 },
  { n:98, section:"Nervous System", text:"The autonomic nervous system strictly controls \"involuntary\" effectors. Which of the following tissues is functionally innervated and controlled by the autonomic nervous system?", options:["The dense regular connective tissue of the Achilles tendon.","The simple squamous epithelium of the alveoli.","The heavily striated skeletal muscle fibers of the biceps brachii.","The smooth muscle located in the walls of the blood vessels and digestive tract.","The solid, calcified compact bone of the femur."], answer:3 },
  { n:99, section:"Nervous System", text:"A patient is tested for two-point discrimination on their fingertip versus their shoulder. The examiner finds that the patient can distinguish two points much closer together on the fingertip. Functionally, what does this indicate about the nervous system?", options:["The shoulder entirely lacks any sensory receptors.","The fingertip contains a much higher density of sensory receptors with smaller receptive fields, allowing for highly precise spatial resolution compared to the shoulder.","The skin on the shoulder is too heavily keratinized for electrical signals to penetrate.","The fingertip relies solely on chemical chemoreceptors rather than tactile mechanoreceptors.","Action potentials travel twice as fast from the hand as they do from the torso."], answer:1 },
  { n:100, section:"Bones", text:"During endochondral ossification, the primary ossification center forms in the center of the diaphysis. Functionally, what specific event triggers the actual bone-building phase in this region?", options:["The rapid, uncontrolled division of the outer epidermal stem cells.","The cartilage model suddenly absorbing massive amounts of water from the amniotic fluid.","The penetration of a nutrient artery into the calcifying cartilage, which brings in the blood supply carrying the vital osteogenic stem cells and osteoblasts necessary to secrete the new bone matrix.","The spontaneous generation of yellow bone marrow inside the solid cartilage.","The secretion of heavy, lubricating synovial fluid into the center of the shaft."], answer:2 },
];
